# FMAttack: Exploiting Authentication Gaps in the CXL Fabric Manager API for Data Destruction and Denial of Service

**M.N. Srivatsa Bharadwaj**  
Samsung Semiconductor Research India (SSRI), Bengaluru, Karnataka, India  

***

## Abstract
Compute Express Link (CXL) 4.0 specifies a Fabric Manager (FM) API to orchestrate multi-tenant memory pools, dynamic capacity regions, and port-based routing across disaggregated CXL fabrics. While the CXL Trusted Execution Environment Security Protocol (TSP) effectively uses hardware configuration locking and data sanitization to guarantee data confidentiality [1, Sec. 11.5.4.8.1, 11.5.4.10.1], the specification explicitly leaves Denial of Service (DoS) attacks out of scope [1, Sec. 11.5.3]. Furthermore, CXL employs permissive language regarding management transport, noting only that FM API commands *may* be transported as MCTP messages [1, Sec. 7.6.3]. Because CXL delegates transport security to external DMTF standards without explicitly mandating SPDM-secured MCTP sessions, the management transport remains dangerously exposed by default. 

In this paper, our analysis uncovers five normative gaps within the CXL specification: the FM API command payload tables lack authentication fields, SPDM-secured MCTP transport is not strictly mandated, and the software routing table maintained by the FM can silently diverge from the hardware routing table inside the CXL switch. By exploiting these gaps under an unauthenticated network attacker threat model, we present four concrete attacks: VPPB-REBIND (ATK-1), PORTDOS (ATK-2), DCDRAIN (ATK-3), and TUNNELSPOOF (ATK-4). These attacks empower an unauthenticated actor to permanently destroy multi-tenant data via hardware sanitization mechanisms and to sever shared physical interconnects. To secure the control plane for CXL 5.0, we propose four complementary hardware and software defenses: hardware-anchored ownership registers, SPDM and RATS attestation binding, orchestrator-signed command tokens, and per-tenant hardware isolation.

**Index Terms**—CXL, Fabric Manager, FMAPI, MCTP, SPDM, multi-tenant, disaggregated memory, dynamic capacity device, denial of service.

