## I. INTRODUCTION
Compute Express Link (CXL) has rapidly become the premier interconnect standard for memory disaggregation in modern hyperscale data centers. The latest CXL 4.0 specification refines Dynamic Capacity Devices (DCD), Port-Based Routing (PBR), and the Fabric Manager (FM) API that orchestrates these vital components. Serving as the control plane for every multi-tenant CXL fabric, the FM API is the exclusive mechanism for allocating memory regions across tenants and binding virtual PCI-to-PCI bridges (vPPBs) to logical devices [1, Sec. 7.6.1]. 

Recent enhancements to the CXL specification—most notably the Trusted Execution Environment Security Protocol (TSP)—have significantly bolstered the architecture against data theft. The TSP mandates SPDM authentication and implements `CONFIG_LOCKED` hardware states for confidential computing workloads [1, Sec. 11.5.4.8.1]. However, this rigorous focus on *confidentiality* has inadvertently created a severe blind spot regarding *availability*. In fact, the CXL security model explicitly concedes that "Denial of service attacks are beyond the scope of this specification" [1, Sec. 11.5.3]. 

This availability gap is compounded by the specification's permissive language regarding management bus security. The CXL standard states that the FM API *may* be transported as MCTP messages [1, Sec. 7.6.3], delegating transport security to external DMTF standards rather than enforcing SPDM-secured sessions for all deployments. In this paper, we demonstrate how an unauthenticated network attacker with access to the Management Component Transport Protocol (MCTP) bus can weaponize CXL's own security mechanisms. By doing so, the attacker can permanently destroy multi-tenant data and exponentially increase the blast radius of an attack across isolated physical heads.

We make the following contributions:
1. We systematically audit the CXL FM API command set, identifying five normative specification gaps (GAP-1 through GAP-5) that leave FM command authentication undefined by the CXL standard [1, Sec. 8.2.10].
2. We prove that the MCTP transport used by the FM API allows any unauthenticated process on the network to issue raw FM commands directly to a CXL switch, bypassing the legitimate FM software entirely.
3. We construct four end-to-end attacks (ATK-1 through ATK-4) that exploit these gaps to achieve unblockable denial-of-service, forced-removal data destruction, and command injection.
4. We propose a robust four-layer defense architecture and a concrete standardization roadmap to elevate FM authentication from an optional feature to a mandatory requirement for CXL 5.0.

