## II. BACKGROUND

### A. CXL Architecture and the Fabric Manager
CXL is a cache-coherent interconnect designed to support pooled memory devices accessible by multiple hosts through a CXL fabric switch. The Fabric Manager (FM) is defined as an "external logical process" responsible for configuring this fabric [1, Sec. 7.6.1]. It communicates with CXL switches and devices using the FM API—a set of management commands typically transported over MCTP. The FM API dictates commands for physical port management (opcodes 5100h–510Fh), vPPB management (opcodes 5200h–520Fh), Multi-Logical Device (MLD) management (opcodes 5300h–540Fh), DCD management (opcodes 5600h–5607h), and switch management (opcodes 5700h–5716h) [1, Table 8-397].

### B. SPDM Authentication in CXL
CXL requires devices to support the Security Protocol and Data Model (SPDM) for verifying device identities and establishing secure sessions. Nevertheless, the language governing whether SPDM sessions *must* be used for FM API command transport remains consistently permissive. Transport security is explicitly noted as optional; the standard states only that commands "may be transported as MCTP messages" [1, Sec. 7.6.3], falling short of mandating secured SPDM encapsulation across all deployments.

### C. Dynamic Capacity Devices and Hardware Sanitization
A DCD exposes DC Regions from which the FM allocates memory extents to hosts using `Initiate Dynamic Capacity Add` and `Initiate Dynamic Capacity Release` commands [1, Sec. 7.6.7.6]. Under the TSP, whenever capacity is forcefully removed, the target hardware is strictly mandated to automatically overwrite or cryptographically scramble the data and reset the Trusted Execution (TE) State. This ensures that no data leakage occurs before the capacity is reassigned [1, Sec. 11.5.4.10.1].

