## V. ATTACK DESIGN

### A. ATK-1: vPPB-Rebind (Forced Unbind DoS)
**Objective:** Sever a victim tenant's connection and hijack the routing path.

**Mechanism:** CXL switches fundamentally prohibit the FM from tunneling CXL.io memory requests to any port actively bound to a host [1, Sec. 7.2.3.1]. To bypass this restriction, the unauthenticated attacker issues an `Unbind vPPB` command (Opcode 5202h) [1, Table 8-397] over the MCTP bus. Because SPDM is optional (GAP-2) and the payload lacks an HMAC (GAP-1), the switch executes the command blindly. Once unbound, the port reverts to FM ownership, triggering a Surprise Removal (DoS) for the host. The FM's software routing table now diverges entirely from the hardware state (GAP-3).

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker as Unauthenticated Attacker
    participant Switch as CXL Switch (Hardware)
    participant Victim as Victim Tenant
    Note over Attacker,Switch: No SPDM authentication required (GAP-1, GAP-2)
    Attacker->>Switch: UNBIND_VPPB (opcode 5202h)
    Switch->>Victim: Detach physical binding (Surprise Removal DoS)
    Switch-->>Attacker: UNBIND_RESPONSE
    Attacker->>Switch: BIND_VPPB (opcode 5201h) to attacker LD
    Switch->>Switch: Updates hardware routing table
    Note over Switch: Hardware routing table now diverges<br/>from FM software inventory (GAP-3)
```

### B. ATK-2: PortDoS (Architecturally Sanctioned DoS)
**Objective:** Disable a shared upstream switch port, severing connectivity for all tenants.

**Mechanism:** Capitalizing on the fact that physical port control requires no authentication token (GAP-1), the unauthenticated attacker sends a `Set Physical Port State` command (Opcode 5101h) [1, Table 8-397] to disable the port. Because the specification explicitly accepts DoS as an out-of-scope concern [1, Sec. 11.5.3], the hardware readily complies, instantly taking down the multi-tenant topology.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker as Unauthenticated Attacker
    participant Switch as CXL Switch
    participant Victims as All Tenants on Port
    Attacker->>Switch: GET_PHYSICAL_PORT_STATE (opcode 5100h)
    Switch-->>Attacker: Port list + states
    Attacker->>Switch: SET_PHY_PORT_STATE (opcode 5101h, DISABLED)
    Switch->>Victims: Port physically disabled
    Note over Victims: Massive Denial of Service
```

### C. ATK-3: DCDrain (Forced Removal Data Destruction)
**Objective:** Leverage hardware sanitization to instantly destroy a victim's active memory.

**Mechanism:** The attacker sends an `Initiate Dynamic Capacity Release` (Opcode 5605h) [1, Table 8-397] directly to the DCD device, bypassing the FM entirely (GAP-4). By setting the **Forced Removal** flag (Bit 4) to 1, the attacker triggers the TSP's strict data leakage protections. Under these rules, the hardware is mandated to automatically execute cryptographic scrambling or overwriting and reset the TE state (Sanitize on Release) [1, Sec. 11.5.4.10.1]. Thus, the attacker cleverly leverages the device's own confidentiality mechanisms to permanently destroy the victim's data (such as a live LLM KV-Cache), all without the host OS ever receiving a warning interrupt.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker as Unauthenticated Attacker
    participant DCD as DCD Device Hardware
    participant Victim as Victim Tenant Host
    Note over Attacker,DCD: Direct MCTP access bypasses FM (GAP-4)
    Attacker->>DCD: DCD_RELEASE_CAPACITY (opcode 5605h) + Forced Removal Flag
    Note over DCD: Hardware triggers Sanitize on Release (TSP)
    DCD->>DCD: Cryptographically scrambles / overwrites victim data
    Note over Victim: Live LLM KV-cache memory permanently destroyed.<br/>No OS interrupt generated.
```

### D. ATK-4: TunnelSpoof (The LD Pool CCI Pivot)
**Objective:** Pivot from a single isolated physical Head to gain global management authority over all tenants on a Multi-Headed Device.

**Mechanism:** CXL 4.0 mandates that Multi-Headed Devices expose a global LD Pool CCI accessible via tunneling [1, Sec. 2.5]. The attacker issues the `Tunnel Management Command` (Opcode 5300h) [1, Sec. 7.6.7.3.1]. The outer switch dutifully strips the header and forwards the encapsulated command to the global LD Pool CCI without verifying the inner command's cryptographic authorisation (GAP-5). The attacker successfully pivots out of their isolated physical head, gaining broad execution rights over logical devices assigned to other tenants.

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Attacker as Unauthenticated Attacker
    participant OuterSwitch as Outer CXL Switch
    participant InnerDevice as Global LD Pool CCI (Target)
    Attacker->>OuterSwitch: TUNNEL_MANAGEMENT_COMMAND (opcode 5300h)
    Note over OuterSwitch: Switch strips outer header.<br/>No cryptographic check on inner origin (GAP-5).
    OuterSwitch->>InnerDevice: Forwards encapsulated FM API command
    InnerDevice->>InnerDevice: Executes command (believes it is from FM)
    InnerDevice-->>OuterSwitch: Response
    OuterSwitch-->>Attacker: TUNNEL_RESPONSE
```

