## VI. EVALUATION

### A. Simulation Environment and Results
We implemented a Python-based CXL fabric simulator featuring four primary modules: `FabricModel`, `MCTPBus`, `DCDModel`, and `AttackHarness`. Each attack was executed across 1,000 Monte-Carlo trials, randomizing victim tenant IDs and target ports to ensure rigorous testing. 

Because the CXL specification inherently lacks mandatory payload authentication for these control-plane operations, all four attacks achieved a **100% success rate** in our simulations. While previous iterations of this research extrapolated specific sub-microsecond physical latencies over the SMBus, it is crucial to note that actual execution times will vary heavily depending on the out-of-band physical transport layer utilized (e.g., I2C, I3C, or PCIe VDMs). Regardless of the physical transport speed, the logical success of the attacks is absolutely guaranteed by the current normative rules of the specification.

### B. Limitations
Our proposed software and hardware defenses target control-plane operations (the FM API), which are explicitly decoupled from the high-speed CXL.mem data-plane coherency traffic [1, Sec. 9.20.1]. However, the precise latency overhead introduced by cryptographic token verification and SPDM binding on these specific, infrequent management operations remains unmeasured in silicon and is flagged as a necessary area for future work.

