## VIII. CONCLUSION

While CXL 4.0 successfully guarantees data confidentiality via the Trusted Execution Environment Security Protocol (TSP) [1, Sec. 11.5], its continued reliance on optional transport security leaves the management bus glaringly vulnerable [1, Sec. 7.6.3]. *FMAttack* clearly demonstrates that an unauthenticated network attacker can bypass the Fabric Manager software entirely. By systematically exploiting documented specification gaps, an attacker can issue raw control-plane commands to forcefully unbind tenants, instantly destroy active memory via hardware sanitization, and pivot across isolated physical heads. By implementing mandatory SPDM-secured MCTP binding, orchestrator-signed payload tokens, and hardware-anchored ownership registers, the CXL Consortium has the opportunity to elevate multi-tenant availability to the exact same tier of robust protection as confidentiality for CXL 5.0.

